caption_original: The Supreme Court of Canada has ruled that there is an Aboriginal right to fish for food, social and ceremonial purposes. However, the buying, selling, trading, bartering or the offer to buy, sell, trade or barter Indigenous fishery resources harvested for food, social and ceremonial purposes is not permitted. Fishery Officers investigate any known or suspected incidents of persons engaging in illegal sale of fish and have authority under the Fisheries Act to fine or prosecute offenders.

What is the tallest bird in North America? The Whooping Crane can grow up to 4.9 ft with a 7.5 ft wingspan. 

A record number of the endangered whooping cranes was found in Wood Buffalo National Park during the 2017 nesting survey carried out with the Canadian Wildlife Service. This year’s survey found 98 nests, an increase of 16 over the previous record of 82 set in 2014!
#WildlifeWednesday

caption_original:
Kenow Fire - Waterton Lakes National Park: September 8, 2017; 19:15hr
Parks Canada and RCMP have safely evacuated all residents and non-essential personnel from the park. The Waterton townsite is secured. Admittance at the gate is limited to essential personnel. Intense fire behavior and low visibility caused a risk to safety. To ensure safety, Parks Canada evacuated Waterton.  We understand this is a stressful situation and thank everyone for their cooperation, making this a safe and efficient evacuation process.
The fire did not cross Sage Pass or South Kootenay Pass into the park and helicopters were able to bucket water later in the afternoon. Fire crews enhanced Waterton’s infrastructure and facility protection. Yesterday afternoon we successfully burned out approximately 30 hectares of vegetation near South Kootenay Pass, removing this fuel in anticipation of increasing wind and fire behaviour today. Burning these fuels under calmer conditions increased our chances of holding the fire at this location. Weather conditions are expected to increase fire behaviour for the next two days:
http://www.pc.gc.ca/apps/scond/cond_e.asp?oid=29170&opark=100429

#ScamAlert: Got a call or voicemail from someone claiming to work for the Canada Revenue Agency (CRA) warning you’ll get sued or arrested?

caption_original:
In 1997, a team of hydrographers conducted survey work of Allen Bay, aboard CCGS Henry Larsen. They left a time capsule, ashore, beside one of the benchmarks that they used during the survey. It contained a full crew list and a list of the names of the hydrographic team. Byron Briggs, the current Commanding Officer of CCGS Henry Larsen, was part of that 1997 crew list as the Second Officer. The time capsule was later discovered in 2016 by the Bulford family that was hiking in the area. They contacted the Coast Guard shortly after the discovery, to share news of their find. 

In 2017, the Bulfords will complete the last year of deployment in Resolute Bay and wondered if CCGS Henry Larsen was going to be in the area this summer, and if the ship’s crew wanted to see the time capsule before returning it safely to where it was found before winter set in. A crew change in mid-September of 2017 enabled Captain Briggs to return to the ship, in Resolute Bay, in time to welcome all five Bulford family members onboard the icebreaker.  The time capsule was updated with a 2017 ship’s crew list and a list of CHS hydrographers. The Bulfords also included the story of how/when they found it. Who knows when it will be “rediscovered” or by who? 

Photo caption: A photographic keepsake of a great visit aboard CCGS Henry Larsen. Captain Byron Briggs and the Bulford family. In purple, young Lily is seen holding the time capsule she discovered in 2016.

Fire crews continue to do everything possible to slow the progress of the wildfire and protect critical infrastructure, park resources, and the community of Waterton.

Kenow Fire Information Update – Unified Command: September 11, 2017; 19:15 

FIRE MOVEMENT AND BEHAVIOUR 
• Fire is now firmly established in the Cameron Valley along the Akamina Parkway. 
• There is also fire in the Tamarack Basin which is expected to grow and move into the Blakiston Valley and towards the Red Rock Parkway. 
• We continue to monitor the fire progress. 
• Structural protection units will be activated if necessary. 
• Extensive infrastructure and facility protection is installed within the townsite including high volume pump and sprinkler systems around the perimeter of town. 
• Highways 5 and 6 are now closed at the boundaries of Waterton Lakes National Park. 
• We are expecting similar weather and intense fire behaviour tomorrow. 

SMOKE 
• Intense fire behaviour is generating significant smoke. Wind direction and temperature inversions may result in low-lying smoke in areas north of Waterton, especially at night. 
• Exercise caution while driving in the area, especially at night. Check AB 511 for driving conditions. Speed limits or closures may be put in place. 
• Wildfire smoke affects people differently. People with pre-existing health conditions or sensitivities to air pollution are at risk of worsened symptoms from smoke exposure. For smoke and air quality alerts visit: www.airhealth.ca 

WHAT’S OPEN AND CLOSED… 
• Waterton Lakes National Park is Closed: www.parkscanada.ca/waterton-kenow-fire 
• Calgary Forest Protection Area south of Highway 532 is Closed: http://srd.web.alberta.ca/calgary-area-update

To subscribe or unsubscribe to these updates contact the Fire Information Officer assistant at elisabeth.caron@pc.gc.ca or 819-247-0075. For media inquiries contact the Fire Information Officer at john.stoesser@pc.gc.ca or 403-859-5127. For general inquiries, call our Information Line at 403-859-5109 or kenowfire.waterton@pc.gc.ca

http://www.pc.gc.ca/en/pn-np/ab/waterton/securite-safety/feu-fire-kenow

Our scientists dove two kilometers deep to study previously unexplored underwater mountains off the coast of Vancouver Island: the Union and Dellwood Seamounts.
We used a camera to explore these two extinct volcanoes and the biodiversity hotspots they support. This research will offer insight into their ecological importance and inform how we might better conserve this potential Marine Protect Area. Take a look at what we discovered and celebrate this unique marine habitat.

caption_original: We captured this wonderful moment during Canadian Wildlife Service’s First Annual Mentored Hunt, at Last Mountain Lake National Wildlife Area. Our participants learned so much about ethical and sustainable hunting from our wonderful mentors!With this event, we were able to show people that hunting waterfowl actually helps maintain the population in several ways. Snow Geese, for example, have a current population of over billion. Their nesting grounds are becoming so overpopulated that it is destroying the habitat for other wildlife in the region. Hunting not only helps maintain these populations, but also helps us raise money for conservation, restoration, and enhancement of wildlife habitat in Canada through the purchase of necessary documents such as the Canadian Wildlife Habitat Conservation Stamp.....

caption_original: Thanks to the Oceana Canada and DFO joint expedition, our researchers discovered previously unexplored areas of the Gulf of St. Lawrence. From August 23 to 30, the scientific team sampled and collected scientific data and filmed high-definition footage of the seafloor. Essential information on marine species living in surface waters, such as seabirds, sea turtles and sharks was also collected. This unique experience helped our scientists make major progress to document the richness of the marine environment. Valuable information that will help better protect it! Learn more about the expedition here: http://ow.ly/MLka30f0y6S

caption_original:
During a rare window of opportunity following a safe escort through ice of the French cruise ship LE BORÉAL by CCGS Des Groseilliers, the cruise ship’s captain invited the icebreaker’s captain and some officers, to board LE BORÉAL, to provide interested passengers and crew with an overview of Arctic icebreaking operations. 

Over 100 very eager passengers attended a brief conference where CCGS Des Groseilliers Captain Michel Dufresne, explained how we break ice, how long the ship can stay in the Arctic and other facets of daily life on board an icebreaker.

caption_original: This summer, our scientists returned to Canada’s Arctic Beaufort Sea to learn more about the diverse species that live there. With the support of Inuvialuit experts and collaborators from some of Canada’s top research universities, our researchers are sailing on the F/V Frosti to better understand the relationship between these fish and their extreme environment. During this summer and next, we will sample never before recorded areas of the Beaufort Sea with trawls and science equipment. http://ow.ly/bt9830ffcg4

During this summer and next, we will sample never before recorded areas of the Beaufort Sea with trawls and science equipment.

caption_original: Monarch enthusiasts found a tiny monarch caterpillar on a milkweed plant during a Mission Monarch workshop.We hosted the workshop which was hosted by the Montreal Insectarium at our Big Creek National Wildlife Area in July. caption_original: Greenland sharks are the only sharks that can tolerate the cold Arctic waters. Most Greenland sharks have a parasite, Ommatokoita elongate, that attaches to their eyes, destroys the tissues, and causes partial to complete blindness. The Greenland shark lives in deep water where there is rarely light, so they mainly use their other senses to get around. We have been tagging Greenland sharks as part of the Tremblay Ecosystem Approach project in Nunavut to track their movement and determine their role in the food web.

Be wary of “secret shopper” job opportunities.

While legit secret shopper jobs do exist, there are lots of fake offers for these gigs. Scammers often contact you via spam email claiming that the job is quick and easy AND that it pays well. They then ask you to pay a fee upfront for a bogus “shopping certification.” 

Bottom line? If you have to pay a fee to take on a new job, chances are it’s a scam. http://ow.ly/uaiV30fmsxf

This weekend, Canada and the world celebrated the 30th anniversary of the Montreal Protocol. The Montreal Protocol is a historic international agreement that has eliminated over 99% of substances that were thinning the earth’s ozone layer. 

Like the Paris Agreement, it shows the amazing things we can accomplish when countries work together on a common goal. It’s a reminder of what the world needs to continue to do to address the global threat of climate change.

Do you need to update your relationship status? 

Don’t forget to inform the Canada Revenue Agency (CRA) soon after you get married, have been separated for over 90 days or have been living with a common-law partner for over a year.

CRA will recalculate your benefits and credits based on your adjusted family net income, the province or territory you live in and the number of children you have and their ages. 

Learn more about how to update your marital status and why it’s important: http://ow.ly/85hF30eQM39

Summer is coming to an end, but there are still many days ahead for sailing. Please note that the Canadian Coast Guard’s coastal rescue stations are preparing to phase out their summer activities in Quebec, thus, they will only be in operation until Monday, September 4. After then, services will no longer be offered during weekdays, although, some bases will still be operating during the following three weekends in September: 8-9-10, 15-16-17 and 22-23-24. For full details, see: http://ow.ly/chzK100Msbl 

Please remember, if you go out on Quebec's waterways, make sure to always have the Canadian Coast Guard contact information with you.

caption_original:
During the Tremblay Ecosystem Approach research season in Nunavut, we’ve been lucky enough to spot bowhead whales. Bowheads can weigh between 75 to 100 tons, reach a length of 18 m, and live up to 100 years; yet, can still manage to launch their massive bodies out of the water! Wow! 

Bowheads filter water through baleen by straining the surface of the water to capture zooplankton, which plays a major role in the ecosystem. Researchers hope to determine from food web studies if the whales come for the food, or perhaps simply for a summer break.
caption_cleaned: During the Tremblay Ecosystem Approach research season in Nunavut, we’ve been lucky enough to spot bowhead whales. Bowheads can weigh between to tons, reach a length of m, and live up to years; yet, can still manage to launch their massive bodies out of the water! Wow! Bowheads filter water through baleen by straining the surface of the water to capture zooplankton, which plays a major role in the ecosystem. Researchers hope to determine from food web studies if the whales come for the food, or perhaps simply for a summer break.

caption_original: The ecosystem research team in Tremblay Sound, Nunavut, came across a bird colony! A glaucous gull colony of approximately 25 couples was found on a cliff at the far south of the strait. These birds can nest in different habitats, like cliffs and wetlands. As a result, they have a broad diet. Remains of fish of different sizes and even lemming bones were found, providing a picture of their diet. The cliff offers gull eggs and young birds protection against predators and excellent access to marine resources.

caption_original: Arctic sculpins live in deep and shallow waters where they eat small crustaceans, other small fish and fish larvae. They can tolerate water as cold as -2°C. In order to survive these extreme conditions, they developed a special antifreeze protein to prevent their blood from freezing solid. Sculpins may be a predicator of changes at the bottom of the food web. We collected individuals from two species of sculpins, as part of the ecosystem research project in Tremblay Sound, Nunavut, to better understand their feeding habits, as well as the role they play in the ecosystem.

But we rarely get a view of capelin spawning beyond our beaches. Check out this underwater video!

caption_original:
We are creating a souvenir album celebrating 100 years of bird conservation in Canada. Share with us your bird anecdotes or thoughts on birds today!

The album will be a tribute to birds and all those who love them, volunteer bird observers, or those who have even devoted their career to bird conservation. The album will contain testimonials and photos of 100 people. 

Here’s how to participate :
-Write a 100-word anecdote about your work with birds, bird encounters or about your love of birds.
-Let us know your name and send a self-portrait taken outdoors (300 dpi).
-List your five favorite birds. 
ec.oiseauxmigrateurs-migratorybirds.ec@canada.ca #BirdYear

The album will contain testimonials and photos of people. caption_original:
The Canol Trail is known as one of the world’s most challenging trails. It runs through the Mackenzie Mountains west of Norman Wells, Northwest Territories. The rough terrain includes risks to humans like grizzly bears and fast-moving water. The trail is also a designated contaminated site, due to elements leftover from an old pipeline constructed during the Second World War. 

Recently, a contract was awarded to Englobe Corp. (NWT) to clean up the trail. Remediation of the trail will reduce risks to people, animals and the environment associated with the abandoned pipeline and related infrastructure. This remediation project will benefit the local economy and provide job opportunities to the Sahtu communities. 
To learn more about the Canol Trail Remediation Project, visit: http://ow.ly/r8UJ30fmrCN

The album will be a tribute to birds and all those who love them, volunteer bird observers, or those who have even devoted their career to bird conservation. The album will contain testimonials and photos of 100 people. 

Here’s how to participate :
-Write a 100-word anecdote about your work with birds, bird encounters or about your love of birds.
-Let us know your name and send a self-portrait taken outdoors (300 dpi).
-List your five favorite birds. 
ec.oiseauxmigrateurs-migratorybirds.ec@canada.ca #BirdYear

caption_original:
In 1966, NASA invited scientific groups from around the world to submit proposals to study lunar material from the Apollo 11 mission. The Geological Survey of Canada (GSC) submitted several proposals, and all were accepted!

The GSC received the moon rocks and put them on display to the public. The collection included rock fragments, polished thin sections and soil. There was strong public interest, and long line-ups snaked their way into the GSC’s headquarters at 601 Booth Street!

If you live near Dartmouth, Nova Scotia, come visit Booth #9 at the Bio Expo 2017 this weekend and see how everyday electronics depend on earth’s rare metals.
http://ow.ly/vMFR30fiqJY

The collection included rock fragments, polished thin sections and soil. There was strong public interest, and long line-ups snaked their way into the GSC’s headquarters at Booth Street! caption_original:
The Canadian Transportation Agency's story began 113 years ago.

Its first incarnation – the Board of Railway Commissioners – was established on a snowy day in February 1904 in Ottawa.

As Canada has evolved, our responsibilities and services evolved with it. 
Want to know more? Read At the Heart of Transportation: A Moving History >  http://ow.ly/IsZ530dbqS1

caption_original:
#TravelTips > Know Your Carrier's Limits

Each carrier sets out its own limits for carry-on and checked baggage. Carriers also set time limits for reporting and filing complaints about lost, damaged or delayed baggage. Check your carrier's tariff for its baggage rules and allowances.

 #FlySmart > Top 10 Tips > http://ow.ly/uy2l3061cit

caption_original:
#TravelTips > Call Ahead

From carrying sports equipment and musical instruments, to dietary restrictions, medical conditions and disability-related needs, most carriers require from 48 to 72 hours notice to accommodate special requests.
